         <div class="key-point">
          <h3>How reliable is a mortgage agreement in principle?</h3>
          <p>
            It really depends on how accurate the information you have supplied is, as Banks traditionally do not underwrite documents when a mortgage agreement in principle is submitted many individuals mistakenly enter the wrong information in relation to income and expenditure ie they include bonus income that the Bank or lender will not use or they assume that a car on PCP is not counted as a loan or they include benefit income that will not be considered when the application is fully underwritten. 
          </p>
          <p>
            Due to these types of errors mortgage agreement’s in principle can provide an inflated or deflated indication of how much you could borrow. 
          </p>
          <p>
            Mistakes such as the ones mentioned above can cost weeks of time and could also result in the buyer loosing the property they are trying to purchase. It can also leave the buyer feeling like all hope is lost and that they are not eligible for a mortgage with any lender.
          </p>
          <p>
            At Mortgages Northern Ireland we assess your payslips and Bank Statements before we submit an agreement in principle in order to assure our clients that their agreement in principle is an accurate reflection of the loan amount available to them.
          </p>
          <p>
            The lender best suited to you may not be the one offering the best rate on the market as all lenders assess income in different ways therefore in order to borrow the amount that you require you may be forced to go with one lender or another due to your personal circumstances.
          </p>
         </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container-fluid">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-12">
         <div class="key-point">
          <h3>How long does an agreement in principle last?</h3>
          <p>
            All lenders offer their own version of an agreement in principle but in general they are valid for between 30 – 90 days.
          </p>
          <p>
            You are not committing to a specific lender by applying for an agreement in principle and if they the current aip expires you can generally just resubmit the form and regenerate a new aip which will be valid for another 30 – 90 days.
          </p>
          <p>
            Although most lenders conduct soft searches during the agreement in principle application you should be aware that some still carry out hard searches therefore applying multiple times to various different lenders could result in a negative impact on your credit file.
          </p>
         </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

